                         Workshop Announcement

 DISTRIBUTED DATABASES FOR TELECOMMUNICATIONS

October 26, 1994
Philips Research Labs, Aachen, Germany


The subject of this workshop is the use and impact of database technology
for telecommunications, in particular for new network services in the
Intelligent Network (IN) and the emerging information superhighway.

In the project INDIA (Intelligent Networks as a Data-Intensive Application),
we have developed a distributed database architecture for the
Intelligent Network. This database architecture enables the efficient
definition, deployment and execution of new services.

The one-day workshop gives you the opportunity to familiarize yourself
with the subject, to ask your questions or to contribute your own experience.
Presentations examine the importance of distributed database technology for
telecommunications, introduce the concept of the Intelligent Network and
present the architecture developed in the INDIA project with implementation
details and the achieved results in terms of scalability, increased
availability, fault tolerance, and performance. A demonstration of the
INDIA system shows our realization of the architecture and illustrates
the advantages.


Preliminary programme:

M. Elixmann, Philips Research Laboratories Aachen:
"Trends in Telecommunications"

M. Jarke, RWTH Aachen:
"Distributed Development of Distributed Systems - Principles and Strategies"

K. Klabunde, Philips Research Laboratories Aachen:
"Database Problems in the Intelligent Network" (incl. demonstration)

R. Gallersdoerfer, RWTH Aachen:
"The INDIA Approach" (incl. demonstration)

N. Roussopoulos, University of Maryland, USA:
"Distributed Database Architectures for Telecommunications"

Panel discussion with representatives from industry and science.


The workshop will be held on Oct. 26, 1994, from 9:30 - 16:00, at
Philips Research Labs, Weisshausstr. 2, in Aachen, Germany.
There is a nominal registration fee of DM 30 to defray local costs.

